===Etymology 1===
Shortened from {{m|en|hobby-horse}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|hoby}}, {{m|enm|hobyn}}, {{m|enm|hobin||small horse, pony}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|hobi}}, {{m|fro|*haubi}}, {{m|fro|haubby}}, {{m|fro|hobin}} {{gloss|"a nag, hobby"; > Modern French {{m|fro|aubin}}, Italian {{m|it|ubino}}}}, of {{etyl|gem|en}} origin: from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|hober}}, {{m|fro|ober||to stir, move}}, from {{etyl|odt|en}} {{m|odt|hobben||to toss, move up and down}}; or from {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin related to {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|hoppe||a mare}}, {{etyl|gmq-osw|-}} {{m|gmq-osw|hoppa||a young mare}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{m|frr|hoppe||horse}}; both ultimately from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*huppōną||to hop}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*kewb-||to bend; a bend, joint}}. More at {{l|en|hop}}, {{l|en|hobble}}.

The meaning of ''hobby-horse'' shifted from "small horse, pony" to "child's toy riding horse" to "favorite pastime or avocation" with the connecting notion being "activity that doesn't go anywhere". Possibly originally from a [[proper name]] for a horse, a diminutive of {{m|en|Robert}} or {{m|en|Robin}} (compare {{m|en|dobbin}}).

